{"version":1,"ops":[{"type":1,"author":{"id":"c3437b479c0903710803baccef68d7dfdb4afdaf"},"timestamp":1560697393,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWU0NTY2NTA2NTY=","github-url":"https://github.com/nh2/hatrace/issues/37","origin":"github"},"title":"procToArgv calls doesFileExist instead of checking for a slash","message":"`execvp` work by checking for a slash in the path; if there is a slash, it assumes it is a path (absolute or relative), if there is no slash, it looks it up in PATH.\n\nTherefore the current behaviour of `procToArgv` can be unexpected in that if you run `echo` while having a file called `echo` in current directory, it will run your file, while `execvp` will resolve it through PATH.\n\nOpen question: will `execv` accept a relative path? If it will, the fix is easy, if it will not, weâ€™ll also have to resolve relative paths.","files":null}]}